New York has plenty of talked-about burger spots. Places like Burger Joint and Shake Shack get more media attention here than presidential elections. But conventional wisdom among the experts suggests forgoing these attention hogs and hitting P.J. Clarkes instead. This 129-year-old saloon has occupied the same Upper East Side building since the Chester A. Arthur administration, fending off developers as a forest of gleaming skyscrapers has grown up around it. 
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;PJs cattle are specially selected for the restaurant and their burgers are made from chuck steak ground on-site; the thick-but-not-too-thick patties of obscenely flavorful beef--so tasty theyre only seasoned with salt and pepper--come on classic white buns and are best topped with cheddar and bacon, though the Barnaise Burger (topped with barnaise sauce) is a worthy bite too. Nat King Cole once called P.J.s hamburger the "Cadillac of burgers!"

George Motz writes, "The Apple Pan may serve the best burgers in America." Though he qualifies the may by admitting he doesn't play favorites. This West LA institution opened in 1947 and is the ultimate in early American burger nostalgia, with families, burger hounds and Hollywood celebs all competing for the limited counter space.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;The Apple Pan serves only two burgers, both built from freshly ground quarter-pound patties. The Steakburger comes topped with pickles, mayo, iceberg and sweet relish, while the more popular Hickory Burger loses the relish in favor of barbecue sauce. Both come on a toasted, seedless bun and--in true SoCal fashion--wrapped in wax paper. In-N-Out Burger might be good, but The Apple Pan is better.

A lounge from the fine folks at fire. Small plates. Seasonal menu.
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;I'm not a big fan of small plates or lounges but this city needs more restaurants with seasonal menus.

